h2. Symptoms

After upgrade your JIRA instance to version 4.2 or higher, some custom fields become truncated when viewing the selected options.
\\ !fixed_size_field.png!

h2. Cause

This occurs because after version 4.2, the CSS responsible for displaying the options of custom fields provides only a fixed width value (of 250px) to custom fields. Custom fields that ship with JIRA are fixed for this change, but custom fields from third party plugins may experience the issue.

h2. Resolution

This is resolved in JRA-24112 and JRA-36062.

h2. Workaround

(!) This workaround involves customisations to JIRA which are not supported.

{panel:bgColor=#EAECFF}
# On the filesystem, navigate to _$JIRA_INSTALL/atlassian-jira/WEB-INF/classes/templates/plugins/field/edit/_;
# Choose the custom field type you want to edit and backup the related file. (e.g. Single Select List: *edit-select.vm*);
# Find the *select* attribute line (e.g. _<select class="select" name="$customField.id" id="$customField.id">_) and add the parameter *style="width:auto"* inside it. (e.g. _<select class="select" name="$customField.id" id="$customField.id" style="width:auto">_);
# Save your modifications and restart JIRA. All of your custom fields of that type will then display with the customized CSS from step 3.
{panel}

Hi Guys,

I have just hit a case where I have a JIRA instance hooked up to LDAP and a bunch of users have been deleted underneath JIRA.

I also been using the REST API to retrieve issues from JIRA. 

What now occurs is a nice little 500 when trying to retrieve issues via REST where a user has commented on an issue where that user has been deleted. All the issue fields are fine, since they handle the deleted user just fine, but the underlying CommentImpl does not.

I have worked around this in a patched version of the REST plugin for now, BUT, the fix should occur in the CommentImpl.

Really all usages of UserUtil.* in this class need to be replaced with the much safer call, like what is used in the IssueImpl:

{code}
        if (username != null)
        {
            return OSUserConverter.convertToOSUser(userManager.getUserEvenWhenUnknown(username));
        }
        else
        {
            return null;
        }
{code}

Really returning null sucks pretty hard as well, I would probably just call:

{code}
return OSUserConverter.convertToOSUser(userManager.getUserEvenWhenUnknown(username));
{code}

Which will handle the null username just fine, and return a new ImmutableUser:

{code}
new ImmutableUser.Builder().name(userName).displayName(userName).active(false).toUser();
{code}

Anyway, would love to see this little fix in the next point release ... Peter ?? :)

See you all soon,

Jus

